message.content:
We first need to calculate the following ratios with the given data:

1. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
 • Formula: Main Business Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable  
 • In our statements the beginning Accounts Receivable is 0 and the ending value is 12,792,007.89. Thus:  
  Average Accounts Receivable = (0 + 12,792,007.89) / 2 = 6,396,003.945  
 • Main Business Revenue = 20,318,450.67  
 • Ratio = 20,318,450.67 / 6,396,003.945 ≈ 3.18

2. Operating Cash Flow Ratio (and Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio)  
 • Both are defined here as the ratio of Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities.  
 • Operating Cash Flow = –18,924,462.44  
 • Current Liabilities (from Taxes Payable) = 1,015,922.54  
 • Ratio = –18,924,462.44 / 1,015,922.54 ≈ –18.63  

3. Total Asset Turnover Ratio  
 • Formula: Main Business Revenue / Average Total Assets  
 • Total Assets at beginning = 28,000,000.00 and at end = 30,858,088.75.  
  Average Total Assets = (28,000,000.00 + 30,858,088.75) / 2 = 29,429,044.375  
 • Ratio = 20,318,450.67 / 29,429,044.375 ≈ 0.69

4. Debt to Equity Ratio  
 • Formula: Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity  
 • In the balance sheet the only liabilities given are the current liabilities (Tax Payable) = 1,015,922.54  
 • Total Owner’s Equity = 29,842,166.21  
 • Ratio = 1,015,922.54 / 29,842,166.21 ≈ 0.03

Thus, our computed values are:

{
  "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "3.18",
  "operating cash flow ratio": "-18.63",
  "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-18.63",
  "Total Asset Turnover Ratio": "0.69",
  "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.03"
}
